( 6. Threshold rationale) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The binary decision uses the stronger of two conservative gates: the event is selected) Tj
T*
(when its combined score is at or above the run-specific 97.5th-percentile cutoff) Tj
T*
(\(0.598913 in this run\), or when the rules-only heuristic score reaches 0.62 on its own.) Tj
T*
(The percentile cutoff keeps the submitted bot volume stable for an unlabeled dataset) Tj
T*
(while still letting the anomaly model influence which borderline events enter the review) Tj
T*
(set. The heuristic override prevents high-confidence, explainable rule hits from being) Tj
T*
(missed just because the anomaly ranking moved around after a feature or backend change.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The threshold is not a learned probability boundary. It is an operational cutoff for a) Tj
T*
(review-first workflow where false positives and false negatives are treated as roughly) Tj
T*
(comparable. In this run, the heuristic-only flag rate was 1.39%, while the EIF) Tj
T*
(agreement-tail reference rate was 0.50%; those rates are reported separately so) Tj
T*
(reviewers can see how much each method contributes before the combined decision is) Tj
T*
(applied.) Tj
T*
() Tj
